WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.280
If you haven't heard of TidyVal, I'm about to explain it, but a lot of people have heard

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:19.080
about it and have a certain amount of discomfort and anxiety as evidenced by, for example,

00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:24.240
these two provocatively titled community posts.

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:29.420
And so part of what I want to answer is, like, why are we putting you through this?

00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:35.580
So what is tidy evaluation, and is it going to be bad for your health, something you might

00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:36.580
care about?

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:41.939
And I think part of the reason that so many people know about it but don't know it or

00:00:41.939 --> 00:00:48.419
know about it and fear that they're missing something or that they're behind is this phenomenon

00:00:48.419 --> 00:00:54.259
that I liken to when people become vegan or they start doing CrossFit, they tend to tell

00:00:54.259 --> 00:00:55.900
you about it.

00:00:55.900 --> 00:01:01.380
So when people start learning TidyVal, they tell you about it, and they blog about it

00:01:01.380 --> 00:01:06.239
and they tweet about it, and so it creates in some sense perhaps more general awareness

00:01:06.239 --> 00:01:09.279
than is actually necessary.

00:01:09.279 --> 00:01:15.860
So I'd like to kind of get out ahead of some of this, but first I'd like to undermine my

00:01:15.860 --> 00:01:22.580
whole talk with a list of things that might give you more bang-bang for your buck than

00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:24.760
learning TidyVal.

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:31.959
And this was kind of crowdsourced within the TidyVers team to describe a few things that

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:36.739
you probably want to learn first before you tackle TidyVal.

00:01:36.739 --> 00:01:41.959
So being pretty comfortable writing functions in general would be a really sound thing to

00:01:41.959 --> 00:01:42.959
start with.

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:49.599
I think a lot of people work in a domain like maps or time series or text analysis where

00:01:49.599 --> 00:01:54.919
you have some very effective tooling in your area and getting really up to speed on what

00:01:54.919 --> 00:01:59.879
the bleeding edge is there could be extremely fruitful.

00:01:59.879 --> 00:02:04.800
You know that I'm very into data wrangling, and so I think being comfortable with all

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:10.479
of the different data receptacles in R is really rewarding, especially lists, and being

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:17.440
comfortable putting your lists inside your data frame and this nesting, unnesting paradigm

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:23.080
which is often how this happens, and it's uncomfortable so you often want to get out

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:26.639
of that situation which is the unnesting.

00:02:26.639 --> 00:02:30.199
I'm a big fan of the per programming package.

00:02:30.199 --> 00:02:33.800
It's described as functional programming which is accurate.

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:39.000
I also think a completely fair way to think of it as it's a way to iterate really well

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:46.279
in R with sort of one common pattern, and then I think to elevate any specific set of

00:02:46.279 --> 00:02:52.839
functions here I decided to give the award to the scoped dplyr verbs are probably under

00:02:52.839 --> 00:02:59.440
utilized where you go in and do a mutate or something like that very selectively, like

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:03.600
at certain positions or at certain names.

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:08.279
But if you've decided that indeed you may in fact actually need tidy eval, I'd like

00:03:08.279 --> 00:03:10.440
to demystify it a bit what it is.

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:15.639
So some people here this is more than you needed to know, or like you already know this

00:03:15.639 --> 00:03:21.619
and you're going to love Leonel's talk, and I'm kind of setting that talk up a bit.

00:03:21.619 --> 00:03:23.039
So what is tidy eval?

00:03:23.039 --> 00:03:26.320
I would call it a tool kit for meta programming.

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:30.880
So for a code that writes code or code that mutates code.

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:32.759
And why is it called tidy eval?

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:38.639
So is there something about it that is intrinsically tidy instead of us just like putting tidy

00:03:38.639 --> 00:03:40.399
on everything?

00:03:40.399 --> 00:03:44.839
And I think there is, and it's to explain it would be at a level that's not what this

00:03:44.839 --> 00:03:45.839
talk is about.

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:51.960
But I think closures are an example of there is actually something intrinsically tidy about

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:59.559
the model of changing how evaluation works in the tidy eval world that is like it actually

00:03:59.559 --> 00:04:01.679
really deserves that name.

00:04:01.679 --> 00:04:10.600
But it is also true that the tidyverse itself does a lot of meta programming inside.

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:16.920
And therefore it requires a certain tool kit to exist, and tidy eval powers that.

00:04:16.920 --> 00:04:21.519
So it is also the putting tidy on everything, it's both.

00:04:21.519 --> 00:04:26.179
So if you don't know what I mean by tidy eval does a lot of meta programming, but let's

00:04:26.179 --> 00:04:31.279
just look at a little bit of canonical tidyverse code.

00:04:31.279 --> 00:04:36.959
So here I'm showing working with this Star Wars dataset that comes with dplyr.

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:41.279
I'm doing a little bit of data wrangling with dplyr in that first example, and then

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:46.480
I switch to a different dataset and show you what ggplot2 does.

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:52.000
And I've been talking a lot to Greg Wilson who joined our studio this year, and he's

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.720
really coming from Python, and one of the things we end up talking about a lot is like

00:04:55.720 --> 00:05:01.239
what's up with all these unquoted variable names and everything necessary to make that

00:05:01.239 --> 00:05:06.119
happen and everything necessary to preserve that in your own functions?

00:05:06.119 --> 00:05:13.799
So the lack of quotes around home world, height, highway, color, sorry, class, that

00:05:13.799 --> 00:05:20.079
is brought to you by all the use of meta programming under the hood.

00:05:20.079 --> 00:05:26.959
And here are several equalities that are technically not true, but they're kind of true for the

00:05:26.959 --> 00:05:29.679
duration of my talk, and they're very useful.

00:05:29.679 --> 00:05:34.720
So when I'm talking about meta programming here, which is a really general term, I'm

00:05:34.799 --> 00:05:40.079
basically talking about a more R-specific term, I associate with R, maybe it's used

00:05:40.079 --> 00:05:46.559
in other languages, called nonstandard evaluation, NSE, and it's a term you'll see a lot, especially

00:05:46.559 --> 00:05:52.640
once you're sort of walking around in the tidy eval world, and I'm also going to go

00:05:52.640 --> 00:05:56.959
even further and kind of equate that with using unquoted variable names, which is like

00:05:56.959 --> 00:06:03.959
a further abuse of all this, but that's mostly what I'm talking about here.

00:06:03.959 --> 00:06:06.320
So what is nonstandard evaluation?

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:13.519
So every time we evaluate an expression in our environment, an environment or a chain

00:06:13.519 --> 00:06:17.519
of environment is going to be searched for name value binding, so you've got a name of

00:06:17.519 --> 00:06:21.839
something and you need to look up the value currently associated with that.

00:06:21.839 --> 00:06:27.160
And so nonstandard evaluation means you've got this expression, and before you evaluate

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:29.600
it, you mess with it, perhaps.

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:37.000
You might actually edit the expression, and or right before you evaluate it, you manipulate

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.160
this chain of environments so that it's not sort of the default one that everyone would

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:45.880
expect, and then often you're doing both, okay?

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:51.160
And this is what gives you unquoted variable names and working inside the data frame, so

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:56.559
both of those things are going on in like every deep IR function that you use, right?

00:06:56.559 --> 00:07:01.640
It's going to put that data frame first, data mask, and then you're having these unquoted

00:07:01.640 --> 00:07:04.119
variable names.

00:07:04.119 --> 00:07:09.880
So any function that accepts an unquoted variable name in a data frame is using an SE under

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:19.040
the hood, so that means if you want to write functions and you have to confront that somehow,

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:23.040
and I'm going to show you that there are different levels of confronting that and how easy or

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:26.160
hard that can feel.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:35.200
This top sentence, it's referring to a phrase I think was about Ruby that said if you make

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:41.200
everything equally easy, you're also making everything equally hard.

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:45.839
So certain things in Ruby were made very easy, and then the bargain you strike is you make

00:07:45.839 --> 00:07:47.200
other things hard.

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:51.399
So the tidyverse struck this bargain in a really, really big way.

00:07:51.399 --> 00:07:55.399
So if you make the direct specification variable names really easy, like people can just type

00:07:55.399 --> 00:08:01.279
them and they don't need to type quotes, it makes indirect specification harder for

00:08:01.279 --> 00:08:07.239
all of us, and it turns out indirect specification still comes up a lot.

00:08:07.239 --> 00:08:13.000
So the two main examples here are like what if you have variable names stored as an object?

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:19.679
You want to drop that in there and drive some deep IR function, or what if a user has passed

00:08:19.679 --> 00:08:23.079
a variable name as a function argument?

00:08:23.079 --> 00:08:25.140
How do you pass it through?

00:08:25.140 --> 00:08:29.660
So these are two pretty mundane examples of where the design of the tidyverse makes

00:08:29.660 --> 00:08:31.859
this harder.

00:08:31.859 --> 00:08:36.780
So is this a problem created by the tidyverse for itself?

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:41.380
And the answer is no, and before I worked for RStudio, I was a professor and I taught

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:48.380
a course on applied statistics, and this example I'm about to show you really comes from teaching

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:51.419
this course, SAT 545.

00:08:51.419 --> 00:08:57.020
So here are four functions in base R that all use nonstandard evaluation, and before

00:08:57.020 --> 00:09:03.099
the tidyverse existed, I was a heavy user of these functions because I liked how fluid

00:09:03.099 --> 00:09:04.099
they were.

00:09:04.099 --> 00:09:07.679
I liked not retyping my data frame name all the time.

00:09:07.679 --> 00:09:15.500
So LM, subset, transform and with are all great examples where this ease of interactive

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:18.659
use was prioritized.

00:09:18.659 --> 00:09:24.859
The problem is if you read the help for subset, transform or which, all of them contain almost

00:09:24.859 --> 00:09:26.500
the exact wording.

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:27.979
This is pulled from one of them.

00:09:27.979 --> 00:09:32.539
It makes it very clear that this is a convenience function that you are really only supposed

00:09:32.539 --> 00:09:38.140
to be using interactively if you're there, sitting there, ready to see the errors, and

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:43.099
if you use it in a programming context, you've been warned that it might have unanticipated

00:09:43.099 --> 00:09:45.500
consequences.

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:50.440
And so you've been kind of warned not to program around those functions.

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:53.260
And I'm going to make this example actually more about LM.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:59.179
So I would teach these students how to do a little bit of data wrangling, data visualization,

00:09:59.179 --> 00:10:03.299
and so they might write a function that fits a quadratic model, and I'm going to use the

00:10:03.299 --> 00:10:04.659
gap minor data in a moment.

00:10:04.659 --> 00:10:10.500
So let's say we want to explain life expectancy as a function of time, of the year.

00:10:10.500 --> 00:10:17.539
This is a super simple model in the LM code that might do this.

00:10:17.539 --> 00:10:21.580
And then I would teach them, like, how do you do this for every country in the gap minor

00:10:21.580 --> 00:10:23.500
data set?

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:28.380
And so they know that they need to wrap LM in a function, and then they drop that into

00:10:28.380 --> 00:10:34.299
some sort of iterative machine, and before the tidyverse existed, we were heavy users

00:10:34.299 --> 00:10:36.500
and teachers of the apply functions.

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:42.200
So here I am dropping that into buy, and indeed it works.

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:47.419
It goes and fits this polynomial model to every country in the gap minor data set.

00:10:47.419 --> 00:10:51.140
And this is where I outsmarted myself.

00:10:51.140 --> 00:10:53.099
So the students were like, okay, this is great.

00:10:53.099 --> 00:10:54.580
I have this function written.

00:10:54.580 --> 00:11:03.539
What if I want to do this now for GDP per capita instead of life expectancy?

00:11:03.539 --> 00:11:08.859
So what if I want to sort of let Y and X be general here?

00:11:08.859 --> 00:11:14.059
So you might hope, many do, that that code right there will work.

00:11:14.059 --> 00:11:17.099
And it won't, okay?

00:11:17.099 --> 00:11:20.539
Here's examples of it not working.

00:11:20.539 --> 00:11:24.299
So if you just put those unquoted variable names in in the usual way and you just cross

00:11:24.299 --> 00:11:28.979
your fingers and hope they get passed through, you get an error.

00:11:28.979 --> 00:11:31.739
If you're like, what if I apply quotes?

00:11:31.739 --> 00:11:34.219
You get a different error.

00:11:34.219 --> 00:11:37.659
So it was around this time usually in the course where I'm like, oh, gosh, we need to

00:11:37.659 --> 00:11:45.059
move on to visualization, and I just I never really answered this question.

00:11:45.059 --> 00:11:46.979
Because this is what the answer would look like.

00:11:46.979 --> 00:11:54.179
So here is an example of me improving that little function so that you can use it in

00:11:54.179 --> 00:11:55.580
the usual way.

00:11:55.580 --> 00:12:00.179
And so I really set myself up for failure in some of the ways that I taught things.

00:12:00.179 --> 00:12:04.020
Because I would show my students these cool functions with nonstandard evaluation, and

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:08.020
then I would teach them how to write functions, and then I was like, but please do not combine

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:09.020
the two.

00:12:09.020 --> 00:12:13.219
Because I couldn't teach them this toolkit.

00:12:13.219 --> 00:12:17.859
But if you put yourself to that pain, you get a function that's actually quite pleasant

00:12:17.859 --> 00:12:22.739
to use, and it does work to be dropped in to buy, for example, in this case.

00:12:22.739 --> 00:12:25.359
And so you can change the variables.

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:28.619
You can still use expressions like year minus 1952.

00:12:28.619 --> 00:12:31.380
So that's pretty cool.

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:37.780
So in Base R, programming around these NSE functions is possible for sure, but it's always

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:43.380
either been explicitly discouraged with those warning messages or just implicitly discouraged

00:12:43.380 --> 00:12:46.780
because it's not made to be very easy.

00:12:46.780 --> 00:12:51.419
So going back to sort of tidyverse history, I've been told I'm allowed to call it there

00:12:51.419 --> 00:12:54.179
was a messy eval era.

00:12:54.179 --> 00:12:58.859
And I hear that there was some thought of maybe not letting people use unquoted variable

00:12:58.859 --> 00:13:02.979
names in the tidyverse, and that was discarded.

00:13:02.979 --> 00:13:08.059
And the first thing that really rolled out is you might remember, and they're still there,

00:13:08.059 --> 00:13:17.260
these functions like AES string instead of AES when you have the variable name as a character.

00:13:17.260 --> 00:13:22.580
Or select underscore versus regular select.

00:13:22.580 --> 00:13:27.340
So the standard evaluation version and the nonstandard evaluation version.

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:32.299
And it just turned out that that was pretty unpredictable for users, and I think not so

00:13:32.299 --> 00:13:34.299
fun to maintain.

00:13:34.299 --> 00:13:35.299
It's not very sustainable.

00:13:35.299 --> 00:13:39.219
It's like, are you going to create two versions of every function in the tidyverse?

00:13:39.219 --> 00:13:43.219
And so that doesn't feel so good.

00:13:43.219 --> 00:13:48.419
So the good news is that the tidyverse did ultimately decide to prioritize usability

00:13:48.419 --> 00:13:54.500
and putting the data mask on, allowing unquoted variable names, allowing you to use unquoted

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:56.460
variables and expressions.

00:13:56.460 --> 00:14:01.340
But the bad news is it made programming around it harder for everyone.

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:06.179
And so the good news and the inevitable news is that there has to be some sort of toolkit

00:14:06.179 --> 00:14:11.460
to use internally to create consistency and for other people to use so they can extend

00:14:11.460 --> 00:14:13.219
things.

00:14:13.219 --> 00:14:15.659
And that's provided by Arlang.

00:14:15.659 --> 00:14:18.580
So this is a package which you may or may not have heard of.

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:23.820
It's kind of like vectors in the sense that ideally most people will not have heard of

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:24.820
Arlang.

00:14:24.820 --> 00:14:26.960
It's more of a developer-focusing package.

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:30.419
So that's where the toolkit lives.

00:14:30.419 --> 00:14:32.099
And other things live there as well.

00:14:32.099 --> 00:14:34.280
But this tidyval toolkit does.

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:38.979
And most people should not need to use Arlang with their bare hands.

00:14:38.979 --> 00:14:43.099
So I'm going to close with a rapid-fire set of scenarios.

00:14:43.099 --> 00:14:47.020
So I'm going to sort of fake what a user might want to do.

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:51.900
And then I'm going to tell you how much tidyval you would need to know.

00:14:51.900 --> 00:15:00.020
So if you want to use existing tidyverse functions to analyze data, you do not need to know tidyval.

00:15:00.020 --> 00:15:02.299
Congratulations.

00:15:02.299 --> 00:15:07.739
Continue on in your sort of blissful existence.

00:15:07.739 --> 00:15:12.739
But if you see that you have a lot of code that looks incredibly duplicated and there's

00:15:12.739 --> 00:15:18.619
common logic and all that's changing is the variable that you're doing something to, you

00:15:18.619 --> 00:15:25.099
probably want to write a function to dry this code out, to reduce the duplication.

00:15:25.099 --> 00:15:26.780
But what if that's rapid...

00:15:26.780 --> 00:15:31.099
What if the duplicated code is using dplyr?

00:15:31.099 --> 00:15:35.179
It is still possible that you do not actually need to know tidyval.

00:15:35.179 --> 00:15:37.700
And pass the dots is the phrase I'm going to say.

00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:40.460
Leonel will show that in much greater detail.

00:15:40.460 --> 00:15:42.739
And you definitely don't need Arlang.

00:15:42.739 --> 00:15:47.179
I'll show one example of this, but it's really more suited to the next talk.

00:15:47.179 --> 00:15:54.460
But so if I wanted to take a data frame in, group it by something unspecified, and do

00:15:54.460 --> 00:16:01.500
a summarize, you could take dots and the signature of your convenience function and pass that

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:03.020
straight through.

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:05.580
And you're keeping up the NSE chain.

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:08.340
You are not the weak link in the chain.

00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:11.260
But you really didn't have to do anything explicitly.

00:16:11.260 --> 00:16:12.900
And indeed that works.

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:19.260
You could take the Star Wars data and group by home world or species and it still works.

00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:25.299
Again, you're still in this world where you want to write simple functions to reduce duplication.

00:16:25.299 --> 00:16:28.940
Sometimes your life is not simple enough for pass the dots to get the job done, in which

00:16:28.940 --> 00:16:35.539
case the paradigm you'll need to work with is using a function called nquo, sort of capture

00:16:35.539 --> 00:16:39.140
that unquoted thing and quote it.

00:16:39.140 --> 00:16:44.700
And then at the place you need to mention it, you unquote it with bang, bang, hence

00:16:44.700 --> 00:16:47.380
the really bad dad joke at the beginning.

00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:55.820
So dplyr, ggplot2 and tidyr, for example, all expose this syntax to you.

00:16:55.820 --> 00:16:57.460
And that's why you don't need to know Arlang.

00:16:57.460 --> 00:17:02.299
Because it's really anticipated that people need to use these.

00:17:02.299 --> 00:17:07.420
So here's an example where I need to capture a grouping variable and a summary variable

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:09.619
with this nquo bang, bang pattern.

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:14.619
And the number of arrows on the page here tips you off to why the dot, dot, dot trick

00:17:14.619 --> 00:17:17.500
wouldn't have worked.

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:20.040
And again, this code also works.

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:26.439
And I'm able to change, for example, the variable that I'm summarizing over.

00:17:26.439 --> 00:17:32.959
And so what if you want to make names out of user input?

00:17:32.959 --> 00:17:36.520
You have to use ‑‑ I asked Leonel how do I say this symbol and he's like we call

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:38.239
it colon equals.

00:17:38.239 --> 00:17:43.739
So you need the colon equals thing.

00:17:43.739 --> 00:17:47.560
And again, dplyr, ggplot2 and tidyr will know about this.

00:17:47.560 --> 00:17:49.000
They will make this available.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:52.780
And again, you do not need Arlang.

00:17:52.780 --> 00:17:57.339
And so if you're someone who wants to compute on the expression and you want to manipulate

00:17:57.339 --> 00:18:05.140
environments, I am afraid that you do really need to understand R's evaluation model and

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:09.020
how the tidy eval toolkit manipulates it.

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:13.219
And you will be using Arlang to do that if you're trying to produce something with this

00:18:13.219 --> 00:18:16.739
tidy eval feel.

00:18:16.739 --> 00:18:23.500
I want to give a shout out to a few resources that were helpful to me as background research.

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:28.819
I hope Thomas doesn't mind me pointing this out, but Thomas Lumley wrote something, I'm

00:18:28.819 --> 00:18:34.140
not sure what he would call it, it's clearly not a paper, but this document called standard

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:38.020
nonstandard evaluation back in 2003.

00:18:38.020 --> 00:18:42.859
And it's a nice summary of where things were in BASAR at that time, which was already feeling

00:18:42.939 --> 00:18:47.140
a bit of pain about people are doing NSE different ways.

00:18:47.140 --> 00:18:50.540
And so he does a nice survey of the ways.

00:18:50.540 --> 00:18:56.140
And I imagine this document was meant to generate a conversation and move things towards doing

00:18:56.140 --> 00:18:57.140
it more standard.

00:18:57.140 --> 00:19:02.540
Sort of the BASAR conversation that ultimately is also happening in the tidyverse.

00:19:02.540 --> 00:19:07.739
Then Thomas Miland has a really beautiful pair of blog posts, I think, on explaining

00:19:07.739 --> 00:19:10.939
scoping rules and NSE.

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:15.459
And then Hiroaki Yutani has a beautiful talk, I think, on tidy eval.

00:19:15.459 --> 00:19:20.459
And in particular, he has a great example that builds to the end that really explains

00:19:20.459 --> 00:19:25.699
why tidy eval itself is necessary and it gets at that quality I was hinting at earlier about

00:19:25.699 --> 00:19:30.739
that there is something about tidy eval that's intrinsically tidy.

00:19:30.739 --> 00:19:34.540
Internal resources are from the people who bring you tidy eval.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:36.699
These are resources they've written.

00:19:36.699 --> 00:19:43.420
The second edition of Advanced R, which is under development by Hadley, has a whole part

00:19:43.420 --> 00:19:44.420
on metaprogramming.

00:19:44.420 --> 00:19:47.819
So there's several chapters there that are really useful.

00:19:47.819 --> 00:19:54.780
Leonel Henry is working on a book down site, tidyeval.tidyverse.org, that's still a work

00:19:54.780 --> 00:20:00.380
in progress to try to centralize some of this information and put some cookbooks.

00:20:00.380 --> 00:20:06.099
And there's a great RStudio community thread where people submit wild caught examples.

00:20:06.099 --> 00:20:09.540
And then Hadley and Leonel tell them that they don't actually need to use tidy eval.

00:20:09.540 --> 00:20:15.099
So it's a nice little miniature code makeover thread to look over.

00:20:15.099 --> 00:20:16.099
All right.

00:20:16.099 --> 00:20:16.099


